, by present designation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33F6565FF97FFE1FF7B6B3FE698FCC7" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8B9A36EEFF97FFE1FF7B6B3FE698FCC7" blockId="11.[151,1436,330,1370]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis id="B951EAFCFF97FFE1FF7B6B3FE758FEEC" bold="true" box="[151,279,330,356]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Male. 
<emphasis id="B951EAFCFF97FFE1FE876B3FE7E5FEEB" box="[363,426,330,355]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Head</emphasis>
: Face moderately produced, gradually sloped or angled forward from antenna to oral margin (
<figureCitation id="131E2A6BFF97FFE1FF176B05E70BFE02" box="[251,324,368,394]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–12" captionStartId="5.[151,276,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[225,1350,199,1918]" captionTargetId="figure-44@5.[224,1358,179,1918]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7–12. Male heads, lateral. 7. Afroestricus flavipes (Loew); 8. Cophinopoda pulchripes (Bigot); 9. Longibeccus fuscovittatus (Ricardo); 10. Michotamia coarctata (Macquart); 11. Ommatius neotenellus Bromley; 12. Pygommatius litoreus (Scarbrough &amp; Marascia)." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
); bristles limited to lower 1/2 of face, only short setae dorsally. Flagellum (
<figureCitation id="131E2A6BFF97FFE1FB296B05E343FE02" box="[1221,1292,368,394]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="4.[150,270,1948,1972]" captionTargetBox="[396,1217,190,1930]" captionTargetId="figure-50@4.[384,1225,175,1944]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Male antennae. 1. Afroestricus flavipes (Loew); 2. Cophinopoda pulchripes (Bigot); 3. Longibeccus fuscovittatus (Ricardo); 4. Michotamia coarctata (Macquart); 5. Ommatius neotenellus Bromley; 6. Thallosia congoicola (Oldroyd). Abbr.: flgm=flagellum; ped=pedicel; sc=scape." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
) wider than and as long as scape+pedicel combined; surface sparsely punctuate. Proboscis equal to vertical height of compound eye, slightly compressed medially with vertical height greater than diameter; apex flattened dorsoventrally, awl-shape (
<figureCitation id="131E2A6BFF97FFE1FE396B95E451FE72" box="[469,542,480,506]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–12" captionStartId="5.[151,276,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[225,1350,199,1918]" captionTargetId="figure-44@5.[224,1358,179,1918]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7–12. Male heads, lateral. 7. Afroestricus flavipes (Loew); 8. Cophinopoda pulchripes (Bigot); 9. Longibeccus fuscovittatus (Ricardo); 10. Michotamia coarctata (Macquart); 11. Ommatius neotenellus Bromley; 12. Pygommatius litoreus (Scarbrough &amp; Marascia)." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
). Anterior scutal setae much shorter than scape. 
<emphasis id="B951EAFCFF97FFE1FBB16B95E2D6FE71" box="[1117,1177,480,505]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Wing</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="131E2A6BFF97FFE1FB466B95E342FE72" box="[1194,1293,480,506]" captionStart="FIGURES 30–36" captionStartId="12.[150,271,1898,1922]" captionTargetBox="[154,1435,203,1857]" captionTargetId="figure-61@12.[150,1436,194,1877]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 30–36. Longibeccus fuscovittatus (Ricardo), male wing and terminalia. 30. Right wing; 31–33. Lateral, dorsal and ventral views; 34. Gonostylus; 35–36. Aedeagus, dorsal and lateral views. Abbr.: r4, m3=cells; cerc=cercus; epand=epandrium; epiph= epiphallus; goncx=gonocoxite; hypd=hypandrium; pvapod=posteroventral aedeagal apodeme." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Figs. 30</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="131E2A6BFF97FFE1FAF66B95E374FE72" box="[1306,1339,480,506]" captionStart="FIGURES 41–47" captionStartId="18.[150,268,1749,1773]" captionTargetBox="[151,1431,198,1719]" captionTargetId="figure-196@18.[151,1436,197,1729]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 41–47. Longibeccus imperator (Oldroyd), male, wing and terminalia. 41. Left wing. Figures 42–44. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 45. Gonostylus; 46–47. Aedeagus, dorsal and lateral views. Abbr.: cerc=cercus; distph=disti phallus; epand=epandrium; ep iph=epiphallus; goncx=gon ocoxit e; hypd=hyp andrium; pvapod=posteroventral apodeme." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">41</figureCitation>
): Cell r 
<subScript id="17A134ABFF97FFE1FA786B85E3D3FE76" attach="left" box="[1428,1436,496,510]" fontSize="6" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">1</subScript>
narrowly pointed; base of cell r 
<subScript id="17A134ABFF97FFE1FDE1686DE45AFDAE" attach="left" box="[525,533,536,550]" fontSize="6" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">4</subScript>
at or just before apex of cell d; R 
<subScript id="17A134ABFF97FFE1FC45686DE5FEFDAE" attach="left" box="[937,945,536,550]" fontSize="6" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">4</subScript>
slightly concave apically, joining C at or just below wing apex. 
<emphasis id="B951EAFCFF97FFE1FE406844E796FDC2" box="[428,473,561,586]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Leg</emphasis>
: Metathoracic femur with short, brown, spur-like, anteroventral bristles, about twice as long as ventral setae. 
<emphasis id="B951EAFCFF97FFE1FDE36823E4DCFDE7" box="[527,659,598,623]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Terminalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="131E2A6BFF97FFE1FD496820E575FDE7" box="[677,826,597,623]" captionStart="FIGURES 30–36" captionStartId="12.[150,271,1898,1922]" captionTargetBox="[154,1435,203,1857]" captionTargetId="figure-61@12.[150,1436,194,1877]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 30–36. Longibeccus fuscovittatus (Ricardo), male wing and terminalia. 30. Right wing; 31–33. Lateral, dorsal and ventral views; 34. Gonostylus; 35–36. Aedeagus, dorsal and lateral views. Abbr.: r4, m3=cells; cerc=cercus; epand=epandrium; epiph= epiphallus; goncx=gonocoxite; hypd=hypandrium; pvapod=posteroventral aedeagal apodeme." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Figs. 31–36</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="131E2A6BFF97FFE1FCA46820E5D5FDE7" box="[840,922,597,623]" captionStart="FIGURES 41–47" captionStartId="18.[150,268,1749,1773]" captionTargetBox="[151,1431,198,1719]" captionTargetId="figure-196@18.[151,1436,197,1729]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 41–47. Longibeccus imperator (Oldroyd), male, wing and terminalia. 41. Left wing. Figures 42–44. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 45. Gonostylus; 46–47. Aedeagus, dorsal and lateral views. Abbr.: cerc=cercus; distph=disti phallus; epand=epandrium; ep iph=epiphallus; goncx=gon ocoxit e; hypd=hyp andrium; pvapod=posteroventral apodeme." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">42–47</figureCitation>
): Epandrium deeply excised apically with contrasting shorter dorsal and longer ventral arms, former with several minute denticles along ventral margin. Aedeagal sheath inflated and produced dorsally, forming an epiphallus which extends above and beyond distiphallus in dorsal view. Female (
<figureCitation id="131E2A6BFF97FFE1FDAC68B0E481FD57" box="[576,718,709,735]" captionStart="FIGURES 37–40" captionStartId="13.[151,274,1477,1501]" captionTargetBox="[162,1433,207,1417]" captionTargetId="figure-234@13.[151,1436,194,1456]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 37–40. Longibeccus fuscovittatus (Ricardo), female terminalia. 37–38. Dorsal and ventral views; 39. Spermathecae; 40. Genital fork. Abbr.: cerc=cercus; tg8, tg9=tergite 8, tergite 9; st8=sternite 8." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Figs. 37–40</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="131E2A6BFF97FFE1FD3668B0E567FD57" box="[730,808,709,735]" captionStart="FIGURES 48–51" captionStartId="19.[151,276,1926,1950]" captionTargetBox="[159,1428,693,1895]" captionTargetId="figure-293@19.[151,1436,665,1905]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 48–51. Longibeccus imperator (Oldroyd), female terminalia. 48–49. Dorsal and ventral views; 50. Spermathecae; 51. Genital fork. Abbr.: cerc=cercus; tg8= tergite 8, tg9=tergite 9; st7=sternite 7, st8=sternite 8." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">48–51</figureCitation>
). Sparse, unusually stout, bristles on apical margin of abdominal segments 7. Cerci triangular, broad basally, fused medially, without membranous line between cerci; base of cercus extends ventrally, fusing with ventral lamella. Spermathecae oval, slightly longer than wide.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33F6565FF97FFE1FF2A692FE400FCFD" box="[198,591,858,885]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8B9A36EEFF97FFE1FF2A692FE400FCFD" blockId="11.[151,1436,330,1370]" box="[198,591,858,885]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis id="B951EAFCFF97FFE1FF2A692FE710FCFC" bold="true" box="[198,351,858,884]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Distribution</emphasis>
. Subsaharan Africa.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33F6565FF97FFE1FF2A69F5E340FC12" box="[198,1295,896,922]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8B9A36EEFF97FFE1FF2A69F5E340FC12" blockId="11.[151,1436,330,1370]" box="[198,1295,896,922]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis id="B951EAFCFF97FFE1FF2A69F5E704FC12" bold="true" box="[198,331,896,922]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Etymology</emphasis>
. Latin combination 
<taxonomicName id="4C254D6DFF97FFE1FDD569F4E482FC12" authorityName="Scarbrough" authorityYear="2010" box="[569,717,897,922]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Longibeccus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B951EAFCFF97FFE1FDD569F4E482FC12" box="[569,717,897,922]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Longibeccus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Refers to the long proboscis. Gender masculine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33F6565FF97FFE1FF2A69D0E4B9FAD2" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B9A36EEFF97FFE1FF2A69D0E593FA98" blockId="11.[151,1436,330,1370]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis id="B951EAFCFF97FFE1FF2A69D0E777FC37" bold="true" box="[198,312,933,959]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4C254D6DFF97FFE1FEA069D3E7AFFC37" authorityName="Scarbrough" authorityYear="2010" box="[332,480,934,959]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Longibeccus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B951EAFCFF97FFE1FEA069D3E7AFFC37" box="[332,480,934,959]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Longibeccus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is proposed to accommodate 
<taxonomicName id="4C254D6DFF97FFE1FCB669D3E23BFC37" authorityName="Ricardo" authorityYear="1900" box="[858,1140,934,959]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuscovittatus">
<emphasis id="B951EAFCFF97FFE1FCB669D3E23BFC37" box="[858,1140,934,959]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Ommatius fuscovittatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C254D6DFF97FFE1FB5469D3E31AFC37" authorityName="Oldroyd" authorityYear="1936" box="[1208,1365,934,959]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Longibeccus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imperator">
<emphasis id="B951EAFCFF97FFE1FB5469D3E31AFC37" box="[1208,1365,934,959]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">O. imperator</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It is distinguished by the characters in the key and diagnosis, especially the gently sloped face, unusual shape of the flagellum, long proboscis, wing venation (
<figureCitation id="131E2A6BFF97FFE1FD426985E4B0FB82" box="[686,767,1008,1034]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="4.[150,270,1948,1972]" captionTargetBox="[396,1217,190,1930]" captionTargetId="figure-50@4.[384,1225,175,1944]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Male antennae. 1. Afroestricus flavipes (Loew); 2. Cophinopoda pulchripes (Bigot); 3. Longibeccus fuscovittatus (Ricardo); 4. Michotamia coarctata (Macquart); 5. Ommatius neotenellus Bromley; 6. Thallosia congoicola (Oldroyd). Abbr.: flgm=flagellum; ped=pedicel; sc=scape." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Figs. 3</figureCitation>
, 
